articleBody:
This post is part of Lifehacker&rsquo;s &ldquo;Living With AI&rdquo; series: We investigate the current state of AI, walk through how it can be useful (and how it can&rsquo;t), and evaluate where this revolutionary tech is heading next. Read more here.Almost as soon as ChatGPT launched in late 2022, the world started talking about how and when to use it. Is it ethical to use generative AI at work? Is that &ldquo;cheating?&rdquo; Or are we simply witnessing the next big technological innovation, one that everyone will either have to embrace, or fall behind dragging their feet?AI is now a part of work, whether you like it or notAI, like anything else, is a tool first and foremost, and tools help us get more done than we can on our own. (My job would literally not be possible without my computer.) In that regard, there&rsquo;s nothing wrong, in theory, with using AI to be more productive. In fact, some work apps have fully embraced the AI bandwagon. Just look at Microsoft: The company basically conquered the meaning of &ldquo;computing at work,&rdquo; and it&#039;s adding AI functionality directly into its products.Since last year, the entire Microsoft 365 suite&mdash;including Word, PowerPoint, Excel, Teams, and more&mdash;has adopted &ldquo;Copilot,&rdquo; the company&rsquo;s AI assist tool. Think of it like Clippy from back in the day, only now way more useful. In Teams, you can ask the bot to summarize your meeting notes; in Word, you can ask the AI to draft a work proposal based on your bullet list, then request it tighten up specific paragraphs you aren&rsquo;t thrilled with; in Excel, you can ask Copilot to analyze and model your data; in PowerPoint, you can ask for an entire slideshow to be created for you based on a prompt.These tools don&rsquo;t just exist: They&rsquo;re being actively created by the companies that make our work products, and their use is encouraged. It reminds me of how Microsoft advertised Excel itself back in 1990: The ad presents spreadsheets as time consuming, rigid, and featureless, but with Excel, you can create a working presentation in an elevator ride. We don&rsquo;t see that as &ldquo;cheating&rdquo; work: This is work.




